04156nam a22004935i 9780887553844DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20082008xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875538447 a10.1515/97808875538442doi  a(DE-B1597)664666  a(OCoLC)794867400  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 7aSOC0420002bisacsh04a338.910961 aKrotz, Larry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Uncertain Business of Doing Good :bOutsiders in Africa /cLarry Krotz. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tOutsiders in Africa -- tAngola 1992 -- tLuanda -- tHuambo -- tReportage -- tOther people’s Countries -- tNairobi, kenya 1997 -- tLooking for a Prostitute -- tHawa -- tSearching for Hawa’s Secret -- tHow do you Define Progress? -- tArusha, Tanzania 2002 -- tPastor Ntakirutimana -- tMissionaries for Justice -- tThe Geneva of Africa -- tVerdicts on Rwanda -- tWho goes to Africa? -- tKisumu, Kenya 2004 -- tThe Nyanza Club -- tCircumcising Africa -- tScientific Life -- tThe Uncertain Business of Doing Good -- tLeaving Africa -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe relationship between Westerners and Africa has long been conflicted and complicated. Frequently exploitative, it is also just as often propelled by an almost irresistible urge to ‘do good’. The persistence of this impulse is intriguing. From Doctor Livingstone 150 years ago to the rock star Bono today, outsiders have championed foreign intervention in Africa in political, social, economic, and health care reforms. But underlying all these good intentions, isn’t there a hierarchical belief that we, as outsiders, somehow know what’s best for Africa?As a journalist and documentary filmmaker, Larry Krotz follows the projects of Canadian, American, British and European scientists, NGOs, lawyers, and peacekeepers, all motivated in some manner by the desire to ‘do good’ in Africa. He focuses specifically on people involved in trying to end the Angolan civil war, AIDS research in Kenya, the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda, and the UNIM circumcision research project in Kenya. Along with telling their stories, he examines the ethical and social implications of humanitarian and research projects in Africa, raising many difficult, yet critically important, questions. How have we come to think the way we do about Africa and its people? What has motivated us to action, for good or ill? And, in the face of seemingly insurmountable odds, is there a choice between doing nothing and doing the well-intended, but, perhaps, wrong thing?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755384440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887553844423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887553844/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles